'''D-Bus''' is an inter-process communication (IPC) system for software applications to communicate with one another.

== Installation ==
Portage knows the global USE flag ''dbus'' for enabling support for D-Bus in other packages. Enabling this USE flag will pull in {{Package|sys-apps/dbus}} automatically (default for ''desktop'' [[profile]]s):
{{FileBox|filename=/etc/portage/make.conf|lang=bash|1=
USE="... dbus ..."
}}
The USE flags of dbus are:
{{USEflag|package=sys-apps/dbus
|X+yes
|debug
|doc
|selinux
|static-libs
|systemd
|test
}}

After setting this you want to update your system so the changes take effect:
{{Emerge|params+=--changed-use --deep|@world}}

== Configuration ==
The main config files are the {{Path|/etc/dbus-1/system.conf}} for the system bus and {{Path|session.conf}} for the session bus.

=== Service ===
You can now start D-Bus:
{{RootCmd|/etc/init.d/dbus start}}
To start D-Bus at boot time, add it your default runlevel (although it often also get started by D-Bus depending services):
{{RootCmd|rc-update add dbus default}}

== Usage ==
Some useful commands are:
* <kbd>dbus-monitor --system</kbd> - To monitor the activities in the system bus.
* <kbd>dbus-monitor --session</kbd> - To monitor the activities in the session bus.
* <kbd>dbus-send PARAMETER</kbd> - To send a message. See the ''dbus-send'' [[man page]] for more information.

== Troubleshooting ==
With '''dbus-monitor''' you can monitor the buses. Error are also redirected to Syslog ({{Path|/var/log/messages}}).

